# Coding Standards

## Component Size
No component file should exceed **150 lines**. Split into sub-components when it does.

## Logic Separation
Extract any logic involving `useEffect` or complex `useState` into a custom hook in `src/hooks/`.

```tsx
// BAD — logic mixed into component
function WorkerMap() {
  const [pos, setPos] = useState(null);
  useEffect(() => { navigator.geolocation.watchPosition(p => setPos(p)) }, []);
  return <Map center={pos} />;
}

// GOOD — logic in a hook
function WorkerMap() {
  const pos = useGeolocation();
  return <Map center={pos} />;
}
```

## Performance
- Use `React.memo` for expensive map-marker components.
- Use `next/dynamic` for the Google Maps library to reduce initial bundle size.

## Naming
- Components: **PascalCase** (`ServiceBadge.tsx`).
- Hooks: start with **`use`** (`useGeolocation.ts`).
- Services: **camelCase** (`supabaseClient.ts`).

## Typing
- **No `any`** — use strict TypeScript interfaces from `src/types/`.
- All component props must have an explicit interface.

```tsx
// BAD
function Card({ data }: any) { ... }

// GOOD
interface WorkerCardProps {
  worker: NearbyWorker;
}
function WorkerCard({ worker }: WorkerCardProps) { ... }
```

## Folder Structure
- `/src/constants/` → static values, UI mappings, config (NO API calls, no side effects)
- `/src/services/` → API calls, Supabase clients, external integrations (NO React imports)
- `/src/components/ui/` → small, reusable "dumb" components (Button, Input, Badge)
- `/src/components/features/` → complex "smart" components (WorkerMap, BookingModal)
- `/src/hooks/` → custom React hooks (useGeolocation, useSupabaseAuth)
- `/src/types/` → shared TypeScript interfaces

## Next.js Rules
- Prefer Server Components by default
- Use "use client" only when necessary
- Keep data fetching on the server when possible

## Data Fetching
- Use server-side fetching via `@/services/supabaseServer` when possible
- Use `@/services/supabaseClient` for client-side realtime subscriptions
- Always handle loading and error states

## State Management
- useState → local UI state
- useContext → global lightweight state
- Avoid unnecessary global state

## Error Handling
- Never swallow errors silently
- Use error boundaries for UI crashes
- Log errors to console in development; add monitoring (Sentry) before production

## Accessibility
- Use semantic HTML
- Always include alt text for images
- Ensure keyboard navigation works

## Testing
- Write unit tests for hooks and services
- Write component tests for interactive UI
- Testing framework TBD (add when needed)

## Tooling
- ESLint (with Next.js config)
- Prettier for formatting
- Strict TypeScript mode enabled

## Constants Management
- Avoid magic numbers and hardcoded values inside components
- Extract reusable constants into `/src/constants/`
- Keep feature-specific constants close to the feature (e.g. `constants/map.ts`)
- Allow small, obvious constants inside a file (e.g. `const MAX_RETRIES = 3`)

## SOLID Principles (Applied to React/Next.js)

### Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
- Each component should have one responsibility
- Separate UI, logic (hooks), and data fetching

### Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
- Components should be extendable via props, not modified directly

### Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
- Shared components should behave consistently when reused

### Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
- Avoid large prop interfaces
- Keep props minimal and specific

### Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
- Do not tightly couple components to APIs or services
- Use service layers (`/services/`) for external interactions